  "body": "# submission name:\r\nquantizr\r\n\r\n# upload zipped `archive.zip`\r\n[archive.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/26863641/archive.zip)\r\n\r\n\r\n# report.txt\r\n```\r\n=== Evaluation config ===\r\n  batch_size: 16\r\n  device: cuda\r\n  num_threads: 2\r\n  prefetch_queue_depth: 4\r\n  report: submissions/quantizr/report.txt\r\n  seed: 1234\r\n  submission_dir: submissions/quantizr\r\n  uncompressed_dir: /mnt/d/comma_submission/comma_video_compression_challenge/videos\r\n  video_names_file: /mnt/d/comma_submission/comma_video_compression_challenge/public_test_video_names.txt\r\n=== Evaluation results over 600 samples ===\r\n  Average PoseNet Distortion: 0.00051010\r\n  Average SegNet Distortion: 0.00061113\r\n  Submission file size: 299,970 bytes\r\n  Original uncompressed size: 37,545,489 bytes\r\n  Compression Rate: 0.00798951\r\n  Final score: 100*segnet_dist + √(10*posenet_dist) + 25*rate = 0.33\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\n# does your submission require gpu for evaluation (inflation)?\r\nyes\r\n\r\n# did you include the compression script? and want it to be merged?\r\nyes\r\n\r\n# additional comments\r\nThis challenge kind of nerd sniped me... but I think this is as much as I'm gonna work on this. Also I don't have a good name for this submission. The training script isn't the exact training script I used as I had three different scripts which I ran a few times finetuning the previous best checkpoint. I had an LLM combine the scripts and to make a 5 stage single file pipeline which mimics what I did but I haven't run the entire script to generate a new submission. It should be pretty close though. The training script is also very much not optimized and not performant and it takes a lot longer to train the model than it needs to.\r\nI think sub 0.30 is possible just by sweeping through different conv dims but I don't think its worth the GPU time for me to do so. Further improvement could possibly be made with some neural mask encoding techniques instead of using ffmpeg but I'm not planning on spending more time on this.\r\nChanges made from #53 include dropping optical flow and using Feature-wise Linear Modulation on pose vectors instead of using both masks. As a result the mask video only needs to encode half as many frames and can be done at a higher CRF. Normal convolutions were replaced with depthwise separable convs for parameter efficiency (model is now just 88k params and 64kb when compressed). \r\nThis isn't new to this, but perhaps as a helpful hint to others the training code interpolates (up) the frames -> clamps/rounds -> interpolates (down) to match the evaluation code so that the gradients can compensate for resampling blur due to the aspect ratio changing slightly during interpolation and to compensate for uint8 rounding noise. The training code also shuffles the frame pairs which the original dataloader could not do. \r\n\r\n<img width=\"582\" height=\"437\" alt=\"comparison_4x_new\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6870e5dd-19f1-43db-b568-069d952ea4f4\" />\r\n\r\nInteresting to see that the compressed video almost looks like it has background hills and a daytime sky.\r\n",
